explanation:
For assessing whether any statement in OS_TimerDelete is dead code we must know the semantics and side-effects of all functions, macros, globals and types that affect control flow, side-effects, resource ownership, or timing. Each listed symbol is required for the following reasons:

- OS_ObjectIdToType_Impl: Returns the object type of the current context; determines the early return (OS_ERR_INCORRECT_OBJ_STATE). Must know its possible return values and side-effects to decide if that branch can ever be removed.
- OS_TaskGetId_Impl: Provides the ID passed into OS_ObjectIdToType_Impl. Needed to determine whether the initial context check can ever be true/false.
- OS_ObjectIdGetById: Controls whether the main deletion sequence executes (return_code == OS_SUCCESS). Its return values and side-effects (reference counts, transactions) determine reachability and necessity of downstream code.
- OS_ObjectIdTransferToken: Transfers token ownership between variables. This affects which tokens must be released/finalized; removing related code could change resource lifetime/behaviour.
- OS_TimeBaseLock_Impl / OS_TimeBaseUnlock_Impl: Protect the critical section that manipulates timebase and callback ring. Their presence affects timing and concurrency behaviour (note 1 in MISRA rule). Removing the guarded code or the locks could change behaviour.
- OS_ObjectIdFromToken: Converts a token to an ID used in comparisons/assignments. Needed to understand the values compared/assigned and whether those assignments are redundant.
- OS_ObjectIdEqual: Used to compare IDs; semantics determine whether the conditional branches that update timebase->first_cb are meaningful.
- OS_ObjectIdFinalizeDelete: Performs the finalization of deleting the timecb object (may have notifications, side-effects). Removing its invocation could change program behaviour even if return_code is otherwise unaffected.
- OS_ObjectIdRelease: Releases the timebase token reference. Its side-effects on reference counts/resource lifetime determine whether the release call is necessary (i.e., whether removing it would be dead code).
- OS_ObjectIdDefined: Predicate used before deleting a dedicated timebase. Must know semantics to decide if that conditional and subsequent delete can be removed.
- OS_TimeBaseDelete: Deletes the dedicated timebase. It has non-local side-effects (resource destruction); required to assess whether the call is necessary for correct behaviour.
- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET: Macro used to map tokens/indexes to table entries; needed to understand the memory locations being read/modified (timecb and timebase records).
- OS_timecb_table / OS_timebase_table: Global object tables that are directly modified/read (fields updated). Their layout and aliasing determine whether writes in this function are observable and therefore non-dead.
- OS_object_token_t: Token type used to hold object references/ownership; needed to reason about token copy/transfer semantics and whether token operations have side-effects.
- OS_timecb_internal_record_t: Definition of the timecb record (fields timebase_token, flags, next_cb, prev_cb). Essential to know which writes (resetting next_cb/prev_cb, reading flags) affect global state.
- OS_timebase_internal_record_t: Definition of the timebase record (field first_cb). Required to determine whether assignments to first_cb are observable/necessary.
- TIMECB_FLAG_DEDICATED_TIMEBASE: Flag tested to decide dedicated timebase deletion. Its meaning affects whether dedicated_timebase_id can be set and subsequently deleted.
- OS_OBJECT_ID_UNDEFINED: Used to initialize dedicated_timebase_id and to check/assign undefined IDs; necessary to reason about comparisons and conditions.
- OS_LOCK_MODE_EXCLUSIVE / OS_LOCK_MODE_NONE: Lock mode constants passed to OS_ObjectIdGetById; they influence whether object lookup acquires locks or has side-effects, which matters for timing/behaviour.
- OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_TIMECB / OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_TIMEBASE: Object type constants used in lookups and initial context check; necessary to establish which object tables/behaviours apply.
- memset: Standard initializer used on timebase_token; knowing it is used to initialize token state matters when reasoning about whether later OS_ObjectIdRelease/do-finalize operations are necessary.

Knowing the above symbols (their return values, side-effects, and interactions) is required to determine if any statement(s) in OS_TimerDelete could be removed without changing program behaviour (i.e., are truly dead code).
